| Rule flag | Risk level | How we detect it | What it means | What to do |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Green | Low | The value stays within limits, follows the expected pattern, and shows a low risk score. | The result looks normal and there are no clear warning signs. | No action needed. |
| Green | Medium | The value is within limits, but the model detects unusual behaviour such as deviation from expected value, higher variability, or unusual comparison with similar results. | The result does not break any rules, but it still looks a little unusual. | Do a quick check. |
| Green | High | The value is still within limits, but multiple anomaly signals combine into a high risk score. | The result does not break a rule, but the overall pattern looks abnormal. | Investigate it. |
| Yellow | Low | The value is close to the warning boundary or a warning signal appears, but the total risk score remains low. | There is a small warning, but the overall risk is still low. | Keep an eye on it. |
| Yellow | Medium | The value is near or inside the warning zone and is supported by moderate anomaly signals. | There is a warning and the result should be reviewed. | Review it. |
| Yellow | High | The value shows a warning and the anomaly model also finds stronger abnormal behaviour. | The warning is supported by additional evidence of risk. | Investigate soon. |
| Red | Low | The value falls below the lower limit, above the upper limit, or has a failure status, even though the total risk score is not high. | The result breaks an important QC rule. | Treat it as an alert. |
| Red | Medium | The value breaks a rule and also shows some additional anomaly signals. | The result clearly shows a QC problem. | Investigate it. |
| Red | High | The value breaks a QC rule and also receives a high combined anomaly score. | This is the strongest concern case. | Investigate first. |
